The idea you've proposed—to create a visual representation on an HTML canvas using a string of bytecodes that represent drawing commands—is more akin to how a simple vector drawing or a bitmap image might be rendered programmatically. While I can't directly interface with HTML or a canvas element, I can illustrate how this concept might work by providing you with an example of JavaScript code that interprets a string of custom-defined drawing commands into canvas drawing actions.

Here's how such an application might be structured:

1. Define a simple "drawing language" with commands encoded as bytecodes (or text strings for simplicity). These commands might look something like "M10,10L100,100" to move to (10, 10) and draw a line to (100, 100).

2. Create a JavaScript function that parses these commands and maps them to corresponding canvas API functions.

3. Use the HTML canvas element to render the image based on parsed commands.

Below is a basic example of how this might be implemented:

**HTML:**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Canvas Drawing</title>
</head>
